</span></span></code></div></div></pre>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="8813" data-end="8931">under the side condition that <code data-start="8843" data-end="8846">s</code> is unique in the configuration (or you specify which one via structural congruence).</p>
<p data-start="8933" data-end="8959">This captures the essence:</p>
<ul data-start="8961" data-end="9159">
<li data-start="8961" data-end="9050">
<p data-start="8963" data-end="9050">before: sphere <code data-start="8978" data-end="8981">s</code> is a boundary containing <code data-start="9007" data-end="9010">Q</code>, and the parent process is <code data-start="9038" data-end="9049">pop s . P</code>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="9051" data-end="9159">
<p data-start="9053" data-end="9159">after: the boundary is removed and <code data-start="9088" data-end="9091">Q</code> is placed in parallel at the parent level, then we continue as <code data-start="9155" data-end="9158">P</code>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="9161" data-end="9187">We may later add variants:</p>
<ul data-start="9189" data-end="9270">
<li data-start="9189" data-end="9270">
<p data-start="9191" data-end="9270"><code data-start="9191" data-end="9216">pop s with wiring W . P</code> where <code data-start="9223" data-end="9226">W</code> rebinds the ports in <code data-start="9248" data-end="9251">I</code> to external ports.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="9272" data-end="9275">
<h2 data-start="9277" data-end="9303">6. Summary / Next Steps</h2>
<p data-start="9305" data-end="9317">We now have:</p>
<ul data-start="9319" data-end="9621">
<li data-start="9319" data-end="9396">
<p data-start="9321" data-end="9396">A <strong data-start="9323" data-end="9348">core process calculus</strong> with spheres and pop as first-class constructs.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="9397" data-end="9480">
<p data-start="9399" data-end="9480">A <strong data-start="9401" data-end="9427">formal abstract syntax</strong> suitable for implementation in Lean, Coq, Agda, etc.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="9481" data-end="9549">
<p data-start="9483" data-end="9549">A <strong data-start="9485" data-end="9503">surface syntax</strong> that is readable and roughly π-calculus-like.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="9550" data-end="9621">
<p data-start="9552" data-end="9621">Sketches of typing rules and operational rules for send/recv and pop.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="9623" data-end="9663">If you like this direction, we can next:</p>
<ul data-start="9665" data-end="10228">
<li data-start="9665" data-end="9796">
<p data-start="9667" data-end="9796">Add <strong data-start="9671" data-end="9701">first-class sphere handles</strong> (<code data-start="9703" data-end="9712">v ::= s</code> with type <code data-start="9723" data-end="9734">Sphere(I)</code>), and rules for <em data-start="9751" data-end="9763">remote pop</em> (<code data-start="9765" data-end="9772">pop h</code> where <code data-start="9779" data-end="9782">h</code> is a handle).</p>
</li>
<li data-start="9797" data-end="9934">
<p data-start="9799" data-end="9934">Add <strong data-start="9803" data-end="9824">RSVP-style fields</strong> <code data-start="9825" data-end="9836">(Φ, v, S)</code> attached as metadata to spheres, turning SpherePOP into a tiny executable fragment of the plenum.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="9935" data-end="10067">
<p data-start="9937" data-end="10067">Work out <strong data-start="9946" data-end="9971">categorical semantics</strong> (e.g., spheres as objects, pops as colimits / boundary dissolutions) once the syntax is stable.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="10068" data-end="10228">
<p data-start="10070" data-end="10228">Write a <strong data-start="10078" data-end="10097">Lean definition</strong> of the syntax and reduction rules, then prove basic properties (progress, preservation, confluence in restricted fragments, etc.).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="10230" data-end="10448" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">If you’d like, my next step can be: “give me the Lean inductive definitions for this core syntax and the reduction relation,” and I’ll translate this spec into something closer to your Lean / Simulated Agency pipeline.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="z-0 flex min-h-[46px] justify-start"><div class="touch:-me-2 touch:-ms-3.5 -ms-2.5 -me-1 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-y-4 p-1 select-none touch:w-[calc(100%+--spacing(3.5))] -mt-1 w-[calc(100%+--spacing(2.5))] duration-[1.5s] focus-within:transition-none hover:transition-none touch:pointer-events-auto pointer-events-none [mask-image:linear-gradient(to_right,black_33%,transparent_66%)] [mask-size:300%_100%] [mask-position:100%_0%] motion-safe:transition-[mask-position] group-hover/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-hover/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] group-focus-within/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-focus-within/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] has-data-[state=open]:pointer-events-auto has-data-[state=open]:[mask-position:0_0]" style="mask-position: 0% 0%;"><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Copy" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="copy-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon"><path d="M12.668 10.667C12.668 9.95614 12.668 9.46258 12.6367 9.0791C12.6137 8.79732 12.5758 8.60761 12.5244 8.46387L12.4688 8.33399C12.3148 8.03193 12.0803 7.77885 11.793 7.60254L11.666 7.53125C11.508 7.45087 11.2963 7.39395 10.9209 7.36328C10.5374 7.33197 10.0439 7.33203 9.33301 7.33203H6.5C5.78896 7.33203 5.29563 7.33195 4.91211 7.36328C4.63016 7.38632 4.44065 7.42413 4.29688 7.47559L4.16699 7.53125C3.86488 7.68518 3.61186 7.9196 3.43555 8.20703L3.36524 8.33399C3.28478 8.49198 3.22795 8.70352 3.19727 9.0