in-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1" data-message-model-slug="gpt-5-1"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[1px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="215">Perfect — <strong data-start="10" data-end="49">Option A (deterministic evaluators)</strong> is the correct next foundational step if you want a runnable or provable semantics in Lean. Below is a <strong data-start="153" data-end="210">clean, self-contained, deterministic evaluation layer</strong> for:</p>
<ul data-start="217" data-end="415">
<li data-start="217" data-end="251">
<p data-start="219" data-end="251">arithmetic expressions (<code data-start="243" data-end="250">AExpr</code>)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="252" data-end="283">
<p data-start="254" data-end="283">boolean expressions (<code data-start="275" data-end="282">BExpr</code>)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="284" data-end="315">
<p data-start="286" data-end="315">radius functions (<code data-start="304" data-end="314">RFunExpr</code>)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="316" data-end="340">
<p data-start="318" data-end="340">amplitudes (<code data-start="330" data-end="339">AmpExpr</code>)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="341" data-end="372">
<p data-start="343" data-end="372">mode expressions (<code data-start="361" data-end="371">ModeExpr</code>)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="373" data-end="415">
<p data-start="375" data-end="415">pop expressions (<code data-start="392" data-end="401">PopExpr</code> → <code data-start="404" data-end="414">PopParam</code>)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="417" data-end="434">The design goals:</p>
<ol data-start="436" data-end="965">
<li data-start="436" data-end="544">
<p data-start="439" data-end="544"><strong data-start="439" data-end="458">No placeholders</strong> — every evaluation relation is now <em data-start="494" data-end="500">real</em>, deterministic, and structurally recursive.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="545" data-end="735">
<p data-start="548" data-end="735"><strong data-start="548" data-end="567">Lean-compatible</strong> — I avoid higher-order “λt.E” terms and instead give a deterministic first-order representation that can be extended once your Lean environment includes real analysis.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="736" data-end="858">
<p data-start="739" data-end="858"><strong data-start="739" data-end="753">Executable</strong> — These definitions can be <code data-start="781" data-end="788">#eval</code>ed once you wire in concrete <code data-start="817" data-end="824">Point</code>, <code data-start="826" data-end="832">Time</code>, numeric primitives, etc.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="859" data-end="965">
<p data-start="862" data-end="965"><strong data-start="862" data-end="904">Preserves your original spec structure</strong> — nothing is altered semantically; only made Lean-definable.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p data-start="967" data-end="1037">If you want, I can insert these directly into the canvas file for you.</p>
<hr data-start="1039" data-end="1042">
<h1 data-start="1044" data-end="1110">✔ <strong data-start="1048" data-end="1110">Option A — Deterministic Evaluators for SpherePop Calculus</strong></h1>
<p data-start="1112" data-end="1226">Below is the full evaluation layer.<br data-start="1147" data-end="1150">
It is Lean-like, but I can produce a strictly Lean-4-valid file if you want.</p>
<hr data-start="1228" data-end="1231">
<h1 data-start="1233" data-end="1248">1. <strong data-start="1238" data-end="1248">Values</strong></h1>
<p data-start="1250" data-end="1383">We need a semantic domain. Since your calculus does not mix types dynamically, we only need values for arithmetic and pop parameters.</p>
